      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"adaptation_kind\":\"Restructure\",\"safety_tier\":\"Green\",\"nudge_patch\":null,\"restructure_plan\":{\"revised_weekly_targets\":[{\"week_number\":1,\"weekly_target_km\":32},{\"week_number\":2,\"weekly_target_km\":36},{\"week_number\":3,\"weekly_target_km\":40}],\"revised_current_week_workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":360,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very gently, just getting the legs moving. No pressure on pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":26,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Conversational pace throughout. If legs still feel heavy, it is fine to slow down further.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk or very easy jog to close out.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes of very easy jogging or brisk walking before settling into your easy pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes easy walking or light movement to flush the legs.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The goal here is blood flow and rhythm, not fitness stimulus. Run by feel and let the legs decide the day. If you feel good, that is a bonus — if not, simply logging the time on feet is the win.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run (Tempo Replaced)\",\"target_distance_km\":7,\"target_duration_minutes\":42,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":360,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease in gently, no urgency.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Hold easy, aerobic effort throughout. This replaces the tempo session this week — quality will return once the legs are back.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gentle wind-down.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes very easy to warm up before settling into easy aerobic pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes easy walking or gentle movement.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Rather than asking the legs for threshold effort this week, we are giving them space to recover and rebuild. An easy run here is exactly the right stimulus — it maintains aerobic continuity without adding more fatigue on top of a system that has been signalling it needs a reset.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":5,\"target_duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":375,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":375,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Very easy effort. If the legs still feel flat, this can be a walk-run. The point is gentle movement, not distance.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — the whole run is at recovery intensity.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"A few minutes of easy walking to close out.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"A short, very easy run to keep the legs moving without adding stress. Think of this as active recovery rather than a training session.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Easy Long Run (Reduced)\",\"target_distance_km\":11,\"target_duration_minutes\":66,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":360,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very conservatively, especially in the first couple of kilometres.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Hold easy, conversational pace throughout. No surges, no pushing. Focus on how the legs feel compared to last Sunday.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Wind down gently over the last km.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"8 minutes very easy — let the legs warm up before committing to pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"8 minutes easy walking and gentle movement post-run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This long run is shorter than the original plan but still a meaningful aerobic session. The aim is to come away feeling like you could have kept going — that is the signal we want before resuming normal progression next week. Pace by Daniels-Gilbert zones: stay in the easy zone the entire time.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}],\"forward_path\":\"With this week sitting around 29 km of easy running, the legs get the reset they have been asking for. Week 2 steps up to 36 km, reintroducing one moderate tempo session mid-week (keeping it controlled, well within the Daniels-Gilbert pace-zone index thresholds). Week 3 returns to 40 km, which is where the original plan had Week 1 — so you rejoin the original progression one week later with fresher legs and a better base under you. The sub-1:45 target has plenty of runway across 16 weeks; this reset costs nothing in the long run and likely saves several weeks of compounding fatigue down the road.\"},\"net_load_delta\":-8,\"rationale\":\"Cutting Sunday's long run short when the legs simply had nothing left was the right call — that kind of body awareness is a skill, not a setback. Looking at the past three sessions together, there is a clear pattern: the tempo run ran noticeably slower than the prescribed pace-zone band, Friday's easy run took longer than expected, and then Sunday the legs just switched off. That is not one bad day — it is the body asking for a meaningful reset before it can absorb more training. So here is what I have changed this week: the tempo session on Wednesday becomes an easy aerobic run at the same relaxed pace as Monday, Friday shortens slightly into a genuine recovery run, and Sunday's long run comes down to 11 km — still a real long run, just one that asks the legs to feel good rather than grind through. Weekly volume this week lands around 29 km. From there, Week 2 builds back to 36 km with one controlled tempo session reintroduced, and Week 3 returns to 40 km — exactly where the original plan started. You will rejoin the original progression one week later, with legs that are ready to actually absorb the work. The sub-1:45 goal has plenty of time on the clock; this week is an investment, not a detour.\",\"referral_category\":null}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
